            <P><font face="Arial" size="2"><a name="contdisc"></a><b><font color="#ff0000">Interruption or Permission?</font></b></font>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:pearlstreet@torchlake.com">Mike
            Berst</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">William Ernest Waites' comments about
            spam raise a couple of good points, but I have a different take on
            his conclusions.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Spammers can make money whether or
            not the spam itself generates any sales. All they have to do is
            convince their client that the spam will work, and sell them a
            program of broadcasting UCE.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">There are probably enough businesses
            willing to hire a spammer that the spammer doesn't have to worry
            about customer satisfaction, he can just head down the road to the
            next victim.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Also I think it is a stretch to say
            that the money that businesses pay to spammers is part of the
            Internet economy. In the same way it could be argued that a bank
            robber is part of the economy since he will eventually spend his
            ill-gotten gains with a legitimate business.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Regards,</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Mike Berst&nbsp;<br>
            Apple Journal</font></p>
            <P>
            <a href="mailto:isales@adventive.com">
            <FONT face=Arial size=2>
            <img border="0" src="http://www.audettemedia.com/emailtest/images/comment.gif" width="130" height="20">
            </FONT>
            </a>
            <P align=right><a href="#top"><FONT face=Arial size=2><img border="0" src="http://www.adventive.com/emailtest/images/top.jpg" width="41" height="15">
            </FONT>
            </a></P>
            <FONT face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color=#000000
            size=2>
            <HR>

            </FONT>

            <P><b><font color="#ff0000" face="Arial" size="2">Interruption or Permission?</font></b>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:neil@petemoss.com">Neil
            Schwartzman</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">William Waites wrote:&nbsp;<br>
            <i>While I am no fan of SPAM, this observation only looks at one
            side of the issue. SPAM messages do connect with some interested
            parties. Otherwise, why are all the SPAMMERS doing it?</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">The large spammers are doing it on
            behalf of small, naive companies who know no better. Spammers are
            making a mint promising "confirmed opt-in" messages be
            sent, while aggregating their collections from postings to online
            forums.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>Not just because it's free.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Indeed, exactly because it is free,
            or unrealistically low-cost (robbers have overhead, too -- the
            get-away car needs gas, for instance.) Spammers send millions upon
            millions, with a click-through rate that would get any honest
            marketer fired in a New York minute.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">The resource of names is stolen, the
            resource of the sending computer is stolen (open relays and proxies
            in third-world countries is the predominant manner in which this
            stuff is sent from the U.S., reflected off a computer in Asia, back
            to North America.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>It also is untrue that SPAM
            doesn't pay for the internet. While the SPAM message may not pay for
            passage, somewhere there are servers and designers and writers who
            are making money from the advertising messages some call SPAM. They
            are part of the Internet just as much as bandwidth is.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Then who precisely is paying for the
            bandwidth they are eating up? One freemail service noted that 90% of
            the 1.5 BILLION emails they deal with DAILY is spam. How does the
            spammer have any positive effect on the amount of bandwidth needed
            to deal with that problem?</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Here's another example of a
            small-time domain owner who has to contend with a massive influx of
            spam, robbing him of his bandwidth: <a href="http://striker.ottawa.on.ca/">http://striker.ottawa.on.ca/</a>&nbsp;</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">550,000 attempts to spam, daily. Who
            is paying for that? The domain owner, of course!</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>Sorry. I find SPAM irritating too,
            just as I find some TV commercials, radio commercials, direct mail
            packages, newspaper and magazine ads and outdoor boards offensive if
            they don't serve my immediate need when I see them. Everyone of
            those also places some burden on society. In the end, however, they
            do more to add value than to subtract it.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Hey, I like naked teens as much as
            most people, but I don't consider spam as being a value-addition to
            my email box, nor society in general (with apologies to naked teens
            everywhere). Commercials on TV, radio, newspapers, etc. help to pay
            for the content and infrastructure which is offered to the consumer,
            free of charge, or for a fee lower than the cost of production and
            distribution, and room for profit, of course.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Last time I looked, I am paying for
            my bandwidth, and willingly (grudgingly) accept advertisements in
            the content I get for free or a nominal fee on the Internet. Fair
            trade, and all.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Spammers circumvent that, make no
            contribution to content, and rob us all blind.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Or do you really think that AOL, et
            al, do NOT pass the costs of the increased bandwidth and servers
            they must buy to keep ahead of the spam influx, on to the end user?
            Surely not.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Neil Schwartzman, peteMOSS
            Publications &lt;<a href="http://spamNEWS.com">http://spamNEWS.com</a>&gt;&nbsp;<br>
            &lt;<a href="http://peteMOSS.com">http://peteMOSS.com</a>&gt;&nbsp;<br>
            &lt;<a href="http://spamFLAMES.com">http://spamFLAMES.com</a>&gt;&nbsp;</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">[ Moderator comment ]</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">We can probably agree, as a
            generalisation, that spammers are kept afloat by naive newcomers to
            the Internet, by the greedy brain-dead and by inept corporate
            marketing people who insist on advertising the fact that they
            haven't a clue when it comes to doing their jobs.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I'm not sure where this discussion
            can go from here, really. Let's wrap it up now, unless you have a
            blinding insight that can make a difference.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">YSM</font></p>
            <P>
            <a href="mailto:isales@adventive.com">
            <FONT face=Arial size=2>
            <img border="0" src="http://www.audettemedia.com/emailtest/images/comment.gif" width="130" height="20">
            </FONT>
            </a>
            <P align=right><a href="#top"><FONT face=Arial size=2><img border="0" src="http://www.adventive.com/emailtest/images/top.jpg" width="41" height="15">
            </FONT>
            </a></P>
