            </FONT>

            <P><font face="Arial" size="2"><a name="contdisc2"><FONT color=#000000></FONT></a><b><font color="#ff0000">Libel On The Internet</font></b></font>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:bhoffmann@wsu.edu">Bob
            Hoffmann</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Mark Neely wrote:&nbsp;<i><br>
            (a) It isn't the case that US (or any other publishers) need to be
            apprised of "the libel laws in every country". Truth is
            universal. Truth, as a rule, is a universal defence in such actions.
            The report was erroneous. US publishers, like all others, just need
            to worry about being right.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">While your comment may be consistent
            in its truth content, it is narrowly focused on the issue of libel.
            Let's look at two other scenarios:</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">A U.S. Web site says something
            insulting about a German politician (or rock star), and</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">A U.S. Web site claims that the
            Holocaust is a hoax.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Both of these actions (insult and
            Holocaust revisionism) are legal in the U.S., but illegal in
            Germany. So if I call Helmut Kohl an @$$#*|* on my private U.S. Web
            site, should I be charged with a crime in Germany?</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Perhaps CNN, ABC, and CBS should face
            criminal charges in Iraq for Web site postings that are obviously
            crimes in that country! Those of us who post images of women's faces
            on Web sites should perhaps face charges in Saudi Arabia.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">My point is that libel is just one
            issue. This is even more complicated than the fact that libel is
            differently defined, and the burden of proof is different, in
            various jurisdictions. There are many, many different kinds of
            speech acts that are legal in one location, but prosecutable in
            another. When we accept the fact that a Web site posting in one
            country is subject to libel laws of other countries, we open the
            door to saying that other crimes can be similarly prosecuted -- even
            if they are not crimes in the country where they were posted.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Bob Hoffmann, Web Coordinator<br>
            Information Department<br>
            Cooperative Extension<br>
            Washington State University</font></p>
            <P>
            <a href="mailto:isales@adventive.com">
            <FONT face=Arial size=2>
            <img border="0" src="http://www.audettemedia.com/emailtest/images/comment.gif" width="130" height="20">
            </FONT>
            </a>
            <P align=right><a href="#top"><FONT face=Arial size=2><img border="0" src="http://www.adventive.com/emailtest/images/top.jpg" width="41" height="15">
            </FONT>
            </a></P>
            <FONT face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color=#000000
            size=2>
            <HR>

            </FONT>

            <P><font face="Arial" size="2"><a name="contdisc3"><FONT color=#000000></FONT></a><b><font color="#ff0000">Traffic Boosters</font></b></font>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:jbsmith@igs.net">Jeff
            Smith</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">In Ramon's listing, a product called
            Mailoop was included. I have had some experience with this product,
            though I would not call it a traffic booster so much as it is a
            traffic manager.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Mailoop is one of a few software
            products that attempts to put a simple database and usable front end
            onto various marketing functions including: all incoming and
            outgoing mail, personal autoresponder for automated follow-up email,
            scheduled broadcast messages to all or a sub-section of mail lists,
            and various other email list management functions such as subscribe
            and unsubscribe automation.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">The pitch on profits is more to do
            with online marketers having these campaigns such as follow-up email
            marketing, newsletters, affiliate programs, etc. Mailoop is just one
            of a few tools that can help manage such campaigns.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">A final point -- any half-decent
            software product should offer you a demo version that lets you test
            the software before buying. IMC offers a demo of Mailoop, it's
            really important that users check this out first -- it's a pretty
            heavy system that I found to be a little difficult transferring
            information between other systems. So make sure you like it before
            you buy it.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Hope this helps...</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Jeff Smith<br>
            Secret's Out!<br>
            How To Earn A Fortune With Your Own Information Products&nbsp;<br>
            <a href="http://www.infoproductcreator.com">http://www.infoproductcreator.com</a>&nbsp;</font></p>
            <P>
            <a href="mailto:isales@adventive.com">
            <FONT face=Arial size=2 color="#000000">
            <img border="0" src="http://www.audettemedia.com/emailtest/images/comment.gif" width="130" height="20">
            </FONT>
            </a>
            <P align=right><a href="#top"><FONT face=Arial size=2 color="#000000"><img border="0" src="http://www.adventive.com/emailtest/images/top.jpg" width="41" height="15">
            </FONT>
            </a></P>
            <FONT face="arial, helvetica, sans-serif" color=#000000
            size=2>
            <HR>

            </FONT>

            <P><b><font color="#ff0000" face="Arial" size="2">Traffic Boosters</font></b>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:cvos@netpaths.net">Cayley
            Vos</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">There's a major difference between
            "traffic boosters" and "marketing tools". Save
            your cash and don't buy traffic boosters, automated search engine
            submissions, and anything that offers to submit your site to search
            engines. There is NO WAY you can improve a search engine listing
            without careful efforts by hand.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Marketing tools, such as email
            programs can be effective for promoting your business, providing you
            use them properly and ethically. In my experience, the only way to
            use email marketing is from using a list hand collected by your
            company. If you try to buy lists, you will get complaints, as you
            will be sending unsolicited information to unsuspecting individuals.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">With any product, ask if you can talk
            directly with past customers. Personally I believe that anyone with
            10 pages of marketing hype is selling just that: long winded hype.
            If you cant sell your product in 1 paragraph, you don¹t have a
            product.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Finally, I have found that the
            quality of the seller's website can be an indication of the quality
            of their product, but this is definitely not a rule. I have gotten
            some of my best information from the most unprofessional looking
            websites.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Cayley Vos<br>
            Principal<br>
            <a href="http://netpaths.net">http://netpaths.net</a>&nbsp;<br>
            web hosting | search engine marketing | web development</font></p>
