            <P><b><font color="#ff0000" face="Arial" size="2">Traffic Boosters</font></b>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            From: <a href="mailto:john@4officeautomation.com">John Vorwerk</a></FONT></p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            Hello John and Ramon and fellow I-Salers,

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            First of all, a happy new 2003 to everyone!

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            Ramon, as you have mentioned Mailloop, this of course caught my eye
            as a vendor of a similar (many people say superior) product named
            EmailUnlimited.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            I also use a rather long copy -- not as long as Corey's, but still a
            number of pages. The reason: it works. I have once experimented with
            a shorter, more technical copy, however, had to face a mighty
            decrease in sales and trial download, and immediately switched back
            to long copy again.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            So what is the benefit of using a program like Mailloop or
            EmailUnlimited?

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            Next to sending email announcements and newsletter to your list, the
            best part probably is the follow-up auto responder. It allows you to
            automatically build a relationship to customers.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            You can send personalized emails as if you were drafting them
            manually. You can send download links in case their first down- load
            attempt was interrupted, remind them to read your ebook, offer
            support and ask for feedback (I send automatic HTML surveys).

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            Customers feel comfortable (ok, some say I am getting on their
            nerves ;) ) and I can focus on creating better products. In fact, my
            success as an entrepreneur is based on using autoresponder to
            enhance relationships to customers. And claims that this kind of
            tool can raise revenues by large percentages may sometimes be
            exaggerated, however, a year ago, when I bought a new computer, my
            follow-up system only pretended to work, with the same results as
            switching to short copy: sales plunged deeply.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            So to go directly to your questions:

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            a) So what's out there? I'd say more than a hundred products, most
            of them trash.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            b) Follow-up autoresponders to enhance relationships to your
            customers.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            c) Watch for good support and trial versions. Don't buy a program
            you can't test.

            </FONT>

            </p>
            <p>
            <FONT face="Arial" color=#000000
            size=2>
            d) Gammadyne is reputable, Postmaster is reputable, MailWorkz is
            reputable (although it cannot even send autoresponses), I guess
            Mailloop is reputable, as Ramon mentions it, and Ralph Wilson's
            readers say that I am reputable as well.

            </FONT>

            </p>
